Below is the safest Windows/MSVC way to get Armadillo + ensmallen working together on your machine without vcpkg, without relying on CMake “finding” BLAS/LAPACK, and without building any fragile wrapper libraries.

Key idea (this avoids the exact problem you hit):

Use Armadillo as a “pure template” library and link OpenBLAS directly by defining ARMA_DONT_USE_WRAPPER. Armadillo explicitly supports this.

ensmallen is header-only; the repo explicitly supports “manual install” by copying headers.

This path works especially well when OpenBLAS is in a non-standard location like yours (C:\Program Files (x86)\OpenBLAS). Armadillo’s own FAQ basically recommends the same strategy when OpenBLAS isn’t in a standard location.

1) Exact repos + exact tags to use
Armadillo

Repo: https://gitlab.com/conradsnicta/armadillo-code.git

Tag: 15.2.2

ensmallen

Repo: https://github.com/mlpack/ensmallen.git

Tag: 3.11.0 (released Dec 16, 2025)

Also note: ensmallen requires C++14 and Armadillo ≥ 10.8.2.

2) Pre-flight checks (PowerShell commands that won’t throw “command not found” errors)

Copy/paste these as-is (they only print status).

# --- tools on PATH? (no errors if missing) ---
foreach ($name in "cmake","git","python","cl") {
  $c = Get-Command $name -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue
  if ($c) { Write-Host "[OK] $name -> $($c.Source)" }
  else    { Write-Host "[MISS] $name not found on PATH" }
}

# --- show versions if available (safe) ---
$cm = Get-Command cmake -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue
if ($cm) { & $cm.Source --version | Select-Object -First 1 }

$g = Get-Command git -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue
if ($g) { & $g.Source --version }

$py = Get-Command python -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue
if ($py) { & $py.Source --version }

# --- verify OpenBLAS files exist (safe) ---
$OpenBLASRoot = "C:\Program Files (x86)\OpenBLAS"
Write-Host "`nOpenBLASRoot = $OpenBLASRoot"
foreach ($p in @(
  "$OpenBLASRoot\include\cblas.h",
  "$OpenBLASRoot\include\lapacke.h",
  "$OpenBLASRoot\lib\openblas.lib",
  "$OpenBLASRoot\lib\cmake\OpenBLAS\OpenBLASConfig.cmake"
)) {
  if (Test-Path $p) { Write-Host "[OK] $p" } else { Write-Host "[MISS] $p" }
}

# --- optional: check openblas.lib architecture if dumpbin exists (safe) ---
$db = Get-Command dumpbin -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue
if ($db -and (Test-Path "$OpenBLASRoot\lib\openblas.lib")) {
  & $db.Source /headers "$OpenBLASRoot\lib\openblas.lib" 2>$null | Select-String -Pattern "machine" -First 1
} else {
  Write-Host "[INFO] dumpbin not available (or openblas.lib missing) -> skipping architecture check"
}


If cl is [MISS] in normal PowerShell, you can still build by launching the VS dev environment once per terminal (next step).

3) Ensure MSVC is available in normal PowerShell (safe loader)

Run this in the same terminal before building anything C++ if cl was missing:

$vswhere = "C:\Program Files (x86)\Microsoft Visual Studio\Installer\vswhere.exe"
if (Test-Path $vswhere) {
  $vsPath = & $vswhere -latest -products * -requires Microsoft.VisualStudio.Component.VC.Tools.x86.x64 -property installationPath
  if ($vsPath) {
    $devShell = Join-Path $vsPath "Common7\Tools\Launch-VsDevShell.ps1"
    if (Test-Path $devShell) {
      & $devShell -Arch amd64 -HostArch amd64 | Out-Null
      $cl = Get-Command cl -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue
      if ($cl) { Write-Host "[OK] MSVC ready: $($cl.Source)" } else { Write-Host "[WARN] DevShell ran, but cl still not found" }
    } else {
      Write-Host "[MISS] Launch-VsDevShell.ps1 not found under: $vsPath"
    }
  } else {
    Write-Host "[MISS] vswhere found but no suitable VS/BuildTools instance detected"
  }
} else {
  Write-Host "[MISS] vswhere.exe not found"
}


This avoids the vcpkg-style “cannot locate VS instance” issue by letting Microsoft’s own discovery do the work.

4) Clone the two repos at the exact tags (won’t error if folders already exist)

Pick a deps folder (example: C:\codespace\deps):

$Deps = "C:\codespace\deps"
New-Item -ItemType Directory -Force -Path $Deps | Out-Null
Set-Location $Deps

# Armadillo (tag 15.2.2)
if (-not (Test-Path "$Deps\armadillo-code")) {
  if (Get-Command git -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue) {
    git clone --branch 15.2.2 --depth 1 https://gitlab.com/conradsnicta/armadillo-code.git armadillo-code
  } else {
    Write-Host "[MISS] git not found on PATH"
  }
} else { Write-Host "[SKIP] armadillo-code already exists" }

# ensmallen (tag 3.11.0)
if (-not (Test-Path "$Deps\ensmallen")) {
  if (Get-Command git -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue) {
    git clone --branch 3.11.0 --depth 1 https://github.com/mlpack/ensmallen.git ensmallen
  } else {
    Write-Host "[MISS] git not found on PATH"
  }
} else { Write-Host "[SKIP] ensmallen already exists" }

5) “Install” headers locally (safest) — no CMake detection required

ensmallen explicitly supports manual header install.
Armadillo supports pure-template usage with ARMA_DONT_USE_WRAPPER.

Create a local include bundle:

$Install = Join-Path $Deps "install"
$Inc = Join-Path $Install "include"
New-Item -ItemType Directory -Force -Path $Inc | Out-Null

# Copy Armadillo headers
$ArmaInc = Join-Path $Deps "armadillo-code\include"
if (Test-Path $ArmaInc) {
  Copy-Item -Recurse -Force "$ArmaInc\*" $Inc
  Write-Host "[OK] Copied Armadillo headers -> $Inc"
} else {
  Write-Host "[MISS] Armadillo include dir not found: $ArmaInc"
}

# Copy ensmallen headers (include/ensmallen.hpp and include/ensmallen_bits)
$EnsInc = Join-Path $Deps "ensmallen\include"
if (Test-Path $EnsInc) {
  Copy-Item -Recurse -Force "$EnsInc\*" $Inc
  Write-Host "[OK] Copied ensmallen headers -> $Inc"
} else {
  Write-Host "[MISS] ensmallen include dir not found: $EnsInc"
}


At the end you’ll have:

C:\codespace\deps\install\include\armadillo

C:\codespace\deps\install\include\armadillo_bits

C:\codespace\deps\install\include\ensmallen.hpp

C:\codespace\deps\install\include\ensmallen_bits\...

6) Verify by building a tiny CMake project that links OpenBLAS directly (most robust)

Create a folder anywhere, e.g. C:\codespace\deps\verify:

verify.cpp
#define ARMA_DONT_USE_WRAPPER
#include <armadillo>
#include <ensmallen.hpp>
#include <iostream>

struct Rosenbrock
{
  double Evaluate(const arma::mat& x) const
  {
    const double a = 1.0;
    const double b = 100.0;
    const double t1 = (a - x(0));
    const double t2 = (x(1) - x(0) * x(0));
    return t1*t1 + b*t2*t2;
  }

  void Gradient(const arma::mat& x, arma::mat& g) const
  {
    const double a = 1.0;
    const double b = 100.0;
    g.set_size(2,1);
    g(0) = -2.0*(a - x(0)) - 4.0*b*x(0)*(x(1) - x(0)*x(0));
    g(1) =  2.0*b*(x(1) - x(0)*x(0));
  }
};

int main()
{
  arma::mat x = { {-1.2}, {1.0} };

  ens::L_BFGS opt;
  Rosenbrock f;
  double finalObj = opt.Optimize(f, x);

  std::cout << "finalObj=" << finalObj << "\n";
  std::cout << "x=" << x.t();
  return 0;
}

CMakeLists.txt
cmake_minimum_required(VERSION 3.18)
project(verify_ensmallen_armadillo LANGUAGES CXX)

add_executable(verify verify.cpp)
target_compile_features(verify PRIVATE cxx_std_14)

# header bundle from step 5
target_include_directories(verify PRIVATE "C:/codespace/deps/install/include")

# Disable wrapper and link OpenBLAS directly (most robust on Windows)
target_compile_definitions(verify PRIVATE ARMA_DONT_USE_WRAPPER)

# Link OpenBLAS (MSVC .lib)
target_link_libraries(verify PRIVATE "C:/Program Files (x86)/OpenBLAS/lib/openblas.lib")

Configure + build + run (PowerShell)
$Verify = "C:\codespace\deps\verify"
cmake -S $Verify -B "$Verify\build"
cmake --build "$Verify\build" --config Release
& "$Verify\build\Release\verify.exe"


If that runs, your Armadillo + ensmallen + OpenBLAS toolchain is correct.

Why this is the “safest” path on your setup

ensmallen is header-only and officially supports copying headers directly.

Armadillo officially supports bypassing the runtime wrapper via ARMA_DONT_USE_WRAPPER, in which case you must link BLAS/LAPACK directly (OpenBLAS provides both).

This avoids fragile auto-detection when libraries live under Program Files (x86) and avoids the whole “can’t find LAPACK/BLAS even though installed” failure mode.
